definition.value: A steroid saponin that is 6beta-hydroxytestosterone attached to a alpha-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 6 via glycosidic linkage.
An androstanoid that is testosterone substituted by a alpha-hydroxy group at position 2. A natural product found in Daphnia magna exposed to the biocide tributyltin.
An androstanoid that is  testosterone substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 16. A natural product found in Daphnia magna exposed to the biocide tributyltin.
A D-talopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid that is hexadecanoic acid with unsaturation at positions 4, 7, 10 and 13. It is found in Daphnia galeata.
A  polyunsaturated fatty acid that is icosanoic acid having unsaturation at positions 2, 5, 8, 11, 14 and 17. It has been found in  Daphnia galeata.
A 4-O-beta-D-glucosyl-4-coumaric acid in which the double bond has trans-configuration.
An EC 4.1.2.* (aldehyde-lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of sphinganine-1-phosphate aldolase (EC 4.1.2.27).
An EC 4.1.* (C-C lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any aldehyde-lyase (EC 4.1.2.*).
A cholestanoid that is cholest-4-en-26-oic acid substituted by an alpha-hydroxy group at position 7 and an oxo group at position 3. It is an intermediate metabolite in the bile acid synthesis.
A steroid sulfate that is the 3-sulfate of androsterone.
A Daphnia metabolite produced by the species Daphnia galeata.
An animal metabolite produced by arthropods such as crabs, lobsters, crayfish, shrimps and krill.
A steroid sulfate that is the 3-sulfate of epiandrosterone.
An undecenoate that is the conjugate base of 10-undecenoic acid.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of undecenoic acid.
An apo carotenoid triterpenoid that is 4,4'-diapolycopene in which two of the terminal methyl groups have been oxidised to carboxy groups.
A dodecenoic acid having its double bond in the 5-position.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of dodecenoic acid.
A dodecenoate that is the conjugate base of 5-dodecenoic acid.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as stearoyl.
An apo carotenoid triterpenoid that is 4,4'-diapolycopene in which one of the terminal methyl groups has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
An O-tetradecenoylcarnitine  having 2-tetradecenoyl as the acyl substituent.
A monounsaturated fatty acid that is nonadecanoic acid with a double bond at position 10.
The (Z)-stereoisomer of  10-nonadecenoic acid.
A monounsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 10-nonadecenoic acid.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1D-myo-inositol in which the 1-acyl group is specified as arachidonoyl.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1D-myo-inositol in which the 1-acyl group is specified as stearoyl.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 20:2 in which the acyl group is specified as (11Z,14Z)-icosadienoyl and is located at position 1.
A Daphnia metabolite produced by the species Daphnia magna.
A crustacean metabolite produced by the genus of small planktonic arthropods, Daphnia
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as linoleoyl.
Any salt derived from a member of the class of dithiocarbamic acids by the formal replacement of the hydrogen of the dithiocarboxy group by a metal.
A member of the class of dithiocarbamic acids that is dimethylcarbamic acid in which both of the oxygens are replaced by sulfur.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 3'-end ribonucleotide 3'-phosphate residue.
A octadecadienoic acid with unsaturation at positions 10 and 12 (the 10Z,12Z-stereoisomer).
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any 3'-end ribonucleotide 2',3'-cyclic phosphate residue.
An aromatic amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 3-methylthiophene-2-carboxylic acid with the amino group of 2-amino-1-(4-isopropoxy-2-methylphenyl)-2-methylpropan-1-one.
An octadecadienoate that is the conjugate base of dihomolinoleic acid.
A dipeptide composed of  glycine  and  5-oxo-L-proline joined by a peptide linkage.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any tRNA 3'-terminal nucleotidyl-cytidine residue.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any tRNA 3'-terminal nucleotidyl-cytidyl-cytidine residue; major species at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of benzamides, obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 2-(trifluoromethyl)benzoic acid with the amino group of 2-[3-chloro-5-(trifluoromethyl)pyridin-2-yl]ethylamine. A fungicide used for foiliar application and as a seed treatment in order to control botrystis, powdery mildew and other diseases.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any tRNA 3'-terminal nucleotidyl-cytidyl-cytidyl-adenosine residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An EC 1.3.5.* (oxidoreductase acting on CH-CH of donor with a quinone or related compound as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of succinate dehydrogenase (quinone), EC 1.3.5.1.
An alkyl sulfate that is 7-methyloctyl ester of sulfuric acid.
A semiochemical used for inter-species chemical communication in a way that benefits an individual of another species that receives the chemical signal.
